aws-transcripts.transcript: I was eight years old. I remember that day clearly like it happened just yesterday. My mother is a beady roller. She hand rolls country cigarettes with sustainable family. She's a hard worker and spent 10 to allow us every day rolling beauties. That particular day. She came home and showed me her beauty rolling veg book. She asked me how much money she has earned that week. I went through that book, and what caught my eyes were her palm prints on each page. My mother has never been to school. She uses her Tom Prince instead off a signature to keep recorder for earnings. On that day, for some reason, I wanted to teach her how to hold a pen and write her name. She was reluctant at first. She's my innocently and said no, but deep down I was sure she wanted to give it a tie. With a little bit off participation and a lot of effort, we managed to write her name. Her hands were trembling on her face, was beaming with pride as I watched her do this For the first time in my life, I had a priceless feeling that I could be off some used to this world. That feeling was very special because I am not meant to be useful. In rural India, girls are generally considered worthless. They're a liability or a Borden. If they are considered useful, it is only to come vicious. Keep the house clean. All these children as a second daughter off my conservative Indian family, I was fairly clear from a very early age that no one expected anything from me. I was conditioned to believe that the three identities that defined me poor village girl meant Tak. I wants to live a life off No voice and no choice. These three identities forced me to think that I should never have been born yet. I wa ce all throughout my childhood as I will be these alongside my mother, I would wonder what did my future hold? I often ask my mother with a lot of anxiety. Mama, will my life be different from yours? Well, I have a chance to choose my life. Well, I go to college and she would reply back, Try to finish high school first. I am sure my mother did not mean to discourage me.
